" who struggle to place food on the table and pay rent after their husbands have been deported. Taking us into the homes and schools of children living in increasingly vulnerable circumstances, she presents families that are divided internally, with some children having legal status while their siblings are undocumented. Even children who are U.S. citizens regularly associate immigration with illegality. With vivid ethnographic details and a striking narrative, Everyday Illegal forces us to confront the devastating impacts of our immigration policies as seen through the eyes of children and their families. As legal status influences identity formation, alters the division of power within families, and affects the opportunities children have outside the home, it becomes a growing source of inequality that ultimately touches us all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChildren of immigrantszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aIllegal alienszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aImmigrantsxFamily relationshipszUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aamerican policies.  adaily lives.  adeportation.  aethnographers.  aethnographic study.  aidentity formation.  aillegal immigrants.  aimmigrant children.  aimmigrant experiences.  aimmigrant families.  aimmigrant parents.  aimmigration laws.  aimmigration policies.  alawmakers.  alegal status.  anational identity.  anonfiction.  aparents and children.  asocial historians.  asocial history.  asocial inequality.  atransnational families.  aundocumented families.  aunited states.  aus citizens.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028339840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095927940uhttps://www.de